Okay, I hung up the other nesting box during the day. There it is in its proper place in the garden.
But, a small flashback: "What's inside it?", I hear myself asking.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 2,600mAh 18650 battery cell.
I didn't photograph the battery or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The grey box suspended on the side of the nesting box houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me around 4 hours of energy.
I call that a characteristic. Like that birds can also have a little intimacy.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and orient it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do that when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
